   101→# 2. CREATING AND DESTROYING OBJECTS
   102→## 1. Use STATIC FACTORY METHODS instead of constructors
   103→**_ADVANTAGES_**
   104→
   105→* Unlike constructors, they have names
   106→* Unlike constructors, they are not requires to create a new object each time they're invoked
   107→* Unlike constructors, they can return an object of any subtype of their return type
   108→* They reduce verbosity of creating parameterized type instances
   109→
   110→**_DISADVANTAGES_**
   111→
   112→* If providing only static factory methods, classes without public or protected constructors cannot be subclassed (encourage to use composition instead inheritance).
   113→* They are not readily distinguishable from other static methods (Some common names (each with a different pourpose) are: valueOf, of, getInstance, newInstance, getType and newType)
   114→
   115→```java
   116→
   117→	public static Boolean valueOf(boolean b){
   118→		return b ? Boolean.TRUE :  Boolean.FALSE;
   119→	}
   120→```
   121→
   122→## 2. Use BUILDERS when faced with many constructors
   123→Is a good choice when designing classes whose constructors or static factories would have more than a handful of parameters.
   124→
   125→Builder pattern simulates named optional parameters as in ADA and Python.
   126→
   127→```java
   128→
   129→	public class NutritionFacts {
   130→		private final int servingSize;
   131→		private final int servings;
   132→		private final int calories;
   133→		private final int fat;
   134→		private final int sodium;
   135→		private final int carbohydrate;
   136→
   137→		public static class Builder {
   138→			//Required parameters
   139→			private final int servingSize:
   140→			private final int servings;
   141→
   142→			//Optional parameters - initialized to default values
   143→			private int calories		= 0;
   144→			private int fat 			= 0;
   145→			private int carbohydrate 	= 0;
   146→			private int sodium 			= 0;
   147→
   148→			public Builder (int servingSize, int servings) {
   149→				this.servingSize = servingSize;
   150→				this.servings = servings;
   151→			}
   152→
   153→			public Builder calories (int val) {
   154→				calories = val;
   155→				return this;				
   156→			}
   157→
   158→			public Builder fat (int val) {
   159→				fat = val;
   160→				return this;				
   161→			}
   162→
   163→			public Builder carbohydrate (int val) {
   164→				carbohydrate = val;
   165→				return this;				
   166→			}
   167→
   168→			public Builder sodium (int val) {
   169→				sodium = val;
   170→				return this;				
   171→			}
   172→
   173→			public NutritionFacts build(){
   174→				return new NutritionFacts(this);
   175→			}
   176→		}
   177→
   178→		private NutritionFacts(Builder builder){
   179→			servingSize		= builder.servingSize;
   180→			servings 		= builder.servings;
   181→			calories		= builder.calories;
   182→			fat 			= builder.fat;
   183→			sodium 			= builder.sodium;
   184→			carbohydrate		= builder.carbohydrate;
   185→		}
   186→	}
   187→```
   188→**_Calling the builder_**
   189→```java
   190→
   191→	NutritionFacts cocaCola = new NutritionFacts.Builder(240,8).calories(100).sodium(35).carbohydrate(27).build();
   192→
   193→```
   194→
   195→## 3. Enforce the singleton property with a private constructor or an enum type
   196→There are different ways to create singletons:
   197→
   198→**_Public final field_**
   199→
   200→```java
   201→
   202→	public class Elvis{
   203→		public static final Elvis INSTANCE = new Elvis();
   204→		private Elvis(){...}
   205→		...
   206→		public void singASong(){...}
   207→	}
   208→```
   209→
   210→One problem is that a privileged client can invoke  the private constructor reflectively. Against this attack the constructor needs to be  modified to send  an exception if it is asked to create a second instance.
   211→
   212→**_Singleton with static factory_**
   213→
   214→```java
   215→
   216→	public class Elvis{
   217→		private static final Elvis INSTANCE = new Elvis();
   218→		private Elvis(){...}
   219→		public static Elvis getInstance(){ return INSTANCE; }
   220→		...
   221→		public void singASong(){...}
   222→	}
   223→```
   224→
   225→In this approach it can be change to a non singleton class without changing the class API.
   226→
   227→**_Serialize a singleton_**
   228→
   229→It is needed a _readResolve_ method and declare all the fields _transient_ in addition to the _implements Serializable_ to maintain the singleton guarantee.
   230→
   231→```java
   232→
   233→	private Object readResolve(){
   234→		//Return the one true Elvis and let the garbage collector take care of the Elvis impersonator
   235→		return INSTANCE;
   236→	}
   237→```
   238→
   239→**_Enum Singleton, the preferred approach (JAVA 1.5)_**
   240→
   241→```java
   242→
   243→	public enum Elvis(){
   244→		INSTANCE;
   245→		...
   246→		public void singASong(){...}
   247→	}
   248→```
   249→
   250→Equivalent to the public field, more concise, provides serialization machinery for free, and guarantee against multiple instantiation, even for reflection attacks and sophisticated serialization. _It is the best way to implement a singleton_.
   251→
   252→## 4. Enforce noninstantiability with a private constructor
   253→For classes that group static methods and static fields.  
   254→
   255→Used for example to:
   256→
   257→* Group related methods on primitive values or arrays.
   258→* Group static methods, including factory methods, for objects that implement a particular interface.
   259→* Group methods on a final class instead of extending the class.
   260→
   261→**_Include a private constructor_**
   262→
   263→```java
   264→
   265→	public class UtilityClass{
   266→		// Suppress default constructor for noninstantiability
   267→		// (Add comment to clarify why the constructor is expressly provided)
   268→		private UtilityClass(){
   269→			throw new AssertionError();
   270→		}
   271→		...
   272→	}
   273→```
   274→
   275→## 5. Avoid creating objects
   276→
   277→**REUSE IMMUTABLE OBJECTS**
   278→
   279→**_Don't do this_**
   280→
   281→```java
   282→
   283→	String s = new String("stringette");		
   284→```
   285→
   286→Every call creates a new String instance. The argument *"stringette"* is itself one. This call in a loop would create many of them.
   287→
   288→**_Do this_**
   289→
   290→```java
   291→
   292→	String s = "stringette";		
   293→```
   294→
   295→This one uses a single String instance rather than creating a new one.
   296→
   297→**_Use static factory methods in preference to constructors [Item 1](#1-use-static-factory-methods-instead-of-constructors)_**
   298→
   299→*Boolean.valueOf(String);* Is preferable to the constructor *Boolean(String)*.
   300→
   301→**REUSE MUTABLE OBJECTS THAT WON'T BE MODIFIED**
   302→
   303→**_Don't do this_**
   304→
   305→```java
   306→
   307→	public class Person {
   308→	private final Date birthDate;
   309→	...
   310→		public boolean isBabyBoomer(){
   311→			// Unnecessary allocation of expensive object.
   312→			Calendar gmtCal= Calendar.getInstance(TimeZone.getTimeZone("GMT"));
   313→			gmtCal.set(1946,Calendar.JANUARY,1,0,0,0);
   314→			Date boomStart = gmtCal.getTime();
   315→			gmtCal.set(1965,Calendar.JANUARY,1,0,0,0);
   316→			Date boomEnd = gmtCal.getTime();
   317→			return birthDate.compareTo(boomStart) >= 0 &&birthDate.compareTo(boomEnd)<0;
   318→		}
   319→	}
   320→```
   321→
   322→isBabyBoomer creates a new Calendar,TimeZone and two Date instances each time is invoked.
   323→
   324→```java
   325→
   326→	public class Person {
   327→	private final Date birthDate;
   328→	...
   329→	private static final Date BOOM_START;
   330→	private static final Date BOOM_END;
   331→
   332→	static {
   333→			Calendar gmtCal= Calendar.getInstance(TimeZone.getTimeZone("GMT"));
   334→			gmtCal.set(1946,Calendar.JANUARY,1,0,0,0);
   335→			BOOM_START = gmtCal.getTime();
   336→			gmtCal.set(1965,Calendar.JANUARY,1,0,0,0);
   337→			BOOM_END = gmtCal.getTime();
   338→	}
   339→		public boolean isBabyBoomer(){
   340→			return birthDate.compareTo(BOOM_START) >= 0 &&birthDate.compareTo(BOOM_END)<0;
   341→		}
   342→	}
   343→```
   344→
   345→**_Prefer primitives to boxed primitives, and watch out for unintentional autoboxing_**
   346→
   347→```java
   348→
   349→	//Slow program. Where is the object creation?
   350→	public static void main (String[] args){
   351→		Long sum = 0L;
   352→		for (long i = 0 ; i<= Integer.MAX_VALUE; i++){
   353→			sum+=i;
   354→		}
   355→		System.out.println(sum);
   356→	}
   357→```
   358→
   359→*sum* is declared as *Long* instead of *long* that means that the programs constructs  
   360→ Long instances.
   361→
   362→**_Object polls are normally bad ideas_**
   363→
   364→Unless objects in the pool are extremely heavyweight, like a database connections.
   365→
   366→## 6. Eliminate obsolete object references
   367→**_Can you spot the memory leak?_**
   368→
   369→```java
   370→
   371→	public class Stack{
   372→		private Object[] elements;
   373→		private int size = 0;
   374→		private static final int DEFAULT_INITIAL_CAPACITY = 16;
   375→
   376→		public Stack(){
   377→			elements = new Object [DEFAULT_INITIAL_CAPACITY];
   378→		}
   379→
   380→		public void push(Object e){
   381→			ensureCapacity();
   382→			elements[size++] = e;
   383→		}
   384→
   385→		public Object pop(){
   386→			if (size == 0)
   387→				throw new EmptyStackException();
   388→			return elements[--size];
   389→		}
   390→
   391→		private void ensureCapacity(){
   392→			if(elements.length == size)
   393→				elements = Array.copyOf(elements, 2 * size + 1);
   394→		}
   395→	}
   396→```
   397→
   398→If the stack grows and shrinks the objects popped will not be garbage collected. The stack maintains obsolete references (a reference that will never be dereferenced).
   399→
   400→**_Null out references_**
   401→
   402→```java
   403→
   404→	public pop(){
   405→		if (size == 0)
   406→			throw new EmptyStackException();
   407→		Object result = elements[--size];
   408→		elements[size] = null; // Eliminate obsolete references.
   409→		return result;
   410→	}
   411→```
   412→
   413→Nulling out objects references should be the exception not the norm.  Do not overcompensate by nulling out every object.
   414→
   415→Null out objects only in classes that manages its own memory.
   416→
   417→**_Memory leaks in cache_**
   418→
   419→ Using _WeakHashMap_ is useful when if desired lifetime of cache entries is determined by external references to the key, not the value.
   420→
   421→ Clean oldest entries in cache is a common practice. To accomplish this behaviors, it can be used: background threads, automatically delete older after a new insertion or the _LinkedHashMap_ and its method _removeEldestEntry_.
   422→
   423→**_Memory leaks in listeners and callbacks_**
   424→
   425→If clients register callbacks, but never deregister them explicitly.
   426→
   427→To solve it store only _weak references_ to them, for example storing them as keys in a _WeakHashMap_.
   428→
   429→__Use a Heap Profiler from time to time to find unseen memory leaks__
   430→
   431→## 7. Avoid finalizers
   432→Finalizers are unpredictable, often dangerous and generally.
   433→
   434→**_Never do anything time-critical in a finalizer._**
   435→>There is no guarantee they'll be executed promptly.
   436→
   437→**_Never depend on a finalizer to update critical persistent state._**
   438→>There is no guarantee they'll be executed at all.
   439→
   440→Uncaught exceptions inside a finalizer won't even print a warning.
   441→
   442→There is a severe performance penalty for using finalizers.
   443→
   444→**_Possible Solution_**
   445→
   446→Provide an _explicit termination method_ like the _close_ on  _InputStream_, _OutputStream_, _java.sql.Connection_...
   447→
   448→Explicit termination methods are typically used in combination with the _try-finally_ construct to ensure termination.
   449→```java
   450→
   451→	Foo foo = new Foo(...);
   452→	try {
   453→	    // Do what must be done with foo
   454→	    ...
   455→	} finally {
   456→	    foo.terminate();  // Explicit termination method
   457→	}
   458→```
   459→
   460→**They are good for this two cases**
   461→
   462→* As a safety net. Ask yourself if the extra protection is worth the extra cost.
   463→* Use in native peers. Garbage collector doesn't know about this objects.
   464→
   465→In this cases always remember to invoke super.finalize.
   466→
   467→# 3. METHODS COMMON TO ALL OBJECTS
   468→## 8. Obey the general contract when overriding *equals*
   469→
   470→**_Don't override if:_**
   471→
   472→* Each instance of the class is inherently unique. I.e._Thread_
   473→* You don't care whether the class provides a "logical equality" test. I.e. _java.util.Random_
   474→* A superclass has already overridden _equals_, and the superclass behavior is appropriate for this class I.e. _Set_
   475→* The class is private or package-private, and you are certain  that its _equals_ method will never be invoked
   476→
   477→**_Override if:_**
   478→
   479→A class has a notion of _logical equality_ that differs from mere object identity, and a superclass has not already overridden _equals_ to implement the desired behavior.
   480→
   481→**_Equals implements an "equivalence relation"_**
   482→
   483→* Reflexive: *x.equals(x)==true*
   484→* Symmetric: *x.equals(y)==y.equals(x)*
   485→* Transitive: *x.equals(y)==y.equals(z)==z.equals(x)*
   486→* Consistent: *x.equals(y)==x.equals(y)==x.equals(y)==...*
   487→* Non-nullity: *x.equals(null)->false*
   488→
   489→**_The Recipe_**
   490→
   491→1. Use the == operator to check if the argument is a reference to this object (for performance)
   492→2. Use the _instanceof_ operator to check if the argument has the correct type
   493→3. Cast the argument to the correct type
   494→4. For each "significant" field in the class, check if that field of the argument matches the corresponding field of this object
   495→5. When you are finished writing your _equals_ method, ask yourself three questions: Is it Symmetric? Is it Transitive? Is it Consistent? (the other 2 usually take care of themselves)
   496→
   497→
   498→```java
   499→
   500→	@Override
   501→	public boolean equals (Object o){
   502→		if(o == this)
   503→			return true;
   504→
   505→		if (!(o instanceof PhoneNumber))
   506→			return false;
   507→
   508→		PhoneNumber pn = (PhoneNumber)o;
   509→		return pn.lineNumber == lineNumber
   510→			&& pn.prefix == prefix
   511→			&& pn.areaCode == areaCode;
   512→	}
   513→```
   514→
   515→**_Never Forget_**
   516→
   517→* Always override _hashCode_ when you override _equals_
   518→* Don't try to be too clever (simplicity is your friend)
   519→* Don't substitute another type for _Object_ in the _equals_ declaration
   520→
   521→
   522→## 9. Always override _hashCode_ when you override *equals*
   523→
   524→**_Contract of hashCode_**
   525→
   526→* Whenever _hashCode_ is invoked in the same object it should return the same integer.
   527→* If two objects are equals according to the  _equals_, the should return the same integer calling _hashCode_.
   528→* Is not required (but recommended) that two non _equals_ objects return distinct _hashCode_.
   529→
   530→The second condition is the one that is more often violated.
   531→
   532→**_The Recipe_**
   533→
   534→1. Store constant value i.e. 17 in and integer called _result_.
   535→2. For each field _f_ used in _equals_ do:
   536→  * Compute _c_
   537→    *	boolean: _(f ? 1 : 0)_
   538→    *	byte, char, short or int: _(int) f_
   539→    *	long: _(int) (f ^ (.f >>> 32))_
   540→    *	float: _Float.floatToIntBits(f)_
   541→    *	double: _Double.doubleToLongBits(f)_ and compute as a long
   542→    *	object reference: if _equals_ of the reference use recutsivity, use recursivity for the _hashCode_
   543→    *	array: each element as a separate field.
   544→  * Combine: _result = 31 * result + c_
   545→3. Return _result_
   546→4. Ask yourself if equal instances have equal hash codes.
   547→
   548→```java
   549→
   550→	private volatile int hashCode; // Item 71 (Lazily initialized, cached hashCode)
   551→
   552→	@Override public int hashCode(){
   553→		int result = hashCode;
   554→		if (result == 0){
   555→			result = 17;
   556→			result = 31 * result + areaCode;
   557→			result = 31 * result + prefix;
   558→			result = 31 * result + lineNumber;
   559→			hashCode = result;
   560→		}
   561→		return result;
   562→	}
   563→```
   564→## 10. Always override _toString_
   565→
   566→Providing a good _toString_ implementation makes your class much more pleasant to read.
   567→
   568→When practical, the _toString_ method return all of the  interesting information contained in the object.
   569→
   570→It is possible to specify the format of return value in the documentation.
   571→
   572→Always provide programmatic access to all of the information contained in the value returned by _toString_ so the users of the object don't need to parse the output of the _toString_
   573→
   574→## 11. Override _clone_ judiciously
   575→Cloneable interface does not contain methods
   576→If a class implements Cloneable, Object's clone method returns a field-by-field copy of the object.
   577→Otherwise it throws CloneNotSupportedException.
   578→
   579→If you override the clone method in a nonfinal class, you should return an object obtained by invoking _super.clone_.
   580→A class that implements _Cloneable_ is expected to provide a properly functioning public _clone_ method.
   581→
   582→Simple clone method if object does **not** contain fields that refer to mutable objects.
   583→
   584→```java
   585→
   586→	@Override public PhoneNumber clone() {
   587→		try {
   588→			//PhoneNumber.clone must cast the result of super.clone() before returning it.
   589→			return (PhoneNumber) super.clone();
   590→		} catch(CloneNotSupportedException e) {
   591→			throw new AssertionError(); // Can't happen
   592→		}
   593→	}
   594→```
   595→
   596→If object **contains** fields that refer to mutable objects, we need another solution. Mutable fields will point to same objects in memory and the original and the cloned method will share these objects.
   597→
   598→_clone_ is another constructor and therefore it must ensure not harming the original object and establishing invariants.  
   599→Calling _clone_ recursively in the mutable objects is the easiest way.
   600→
   601→```java
   602→
   603→	@Override public Stack clone() {
   604→		try {
   605→			Stack result = (Stack) super.clone();
   606→			// From Java 1.5, don't need casting when cloning arrays
   607→			result.elements = elements.clone();
   608→			return result;
   609→		} catch (CloneNotSupportedException e) {
   610→			throw new AssertionError();
   611→		}
   612→	}
   613→```
   614→
   615→Mutable objects and finals: The _clone_ architecture is incompatible with normal use of final fields referring to mutable objects.
   616→More complex objects would need specific approaches where recursively calling _clone_ won't work.
   617→
   618→A _clone_ method should not invoke any nonfinal methods on the clone under construction ([Item 17](#17-design-and-document-for-inheritance-or-else-prohibit-it)).
   619→
   620→Object's _clone_ method is declared to throw _CloneNotSupportedException_, but overriding clone methods can omit this declaration.  
   621→Public _clone_ methods should omit it. ([Item 59](#59-avoid-unnecessary-use-of-checked-exceptions)).  
   622→If a class overrides clone, the overriding method should mimic the behavior of _Object.clone_:
   623→
   624→* it should be declared protected,
   625→* it should be declared to throw CloneNotSupportedException,
   626→* it should not implement Cloneable.
   627→
   628→Subclasses are free to implement Cloneable or not, just as if they extended Object directly
   629→
   630→_clone_ method must be properly synchronized just like any other method ([Item 66](#66-synchronize-access-to-shared-mutable-data)).
   631→
   632→Summary: classes that implement Cloneable should create a method that:
   633→
   634→* override clone
   635→* return type is the class
   636→* call _super.clone_
   637→* fix fields that need to be fixed
   638→
   639→Better provide an alternative of object copying, or don't provide it at all.
   640→
   641→**Copy Constructor**
   642→```java
   643→
   644→	public Yum(Yum yum);
   645→```
   646→
   647→**Copy Factory**
   648→```java
   649→
   650→	public static Yum newInstance(Yum yum);
   651→```
   652→These alternatives:
   653→
   654→* don't rely on a risk-prone extra-linguistic object creation mechanism
   655→* don't demand adherence to thinly documented conventions
   656→* don't conflict with the proper use of final fields
   657→* don't throw unnecessary checked exceptions
   658→* don't require casts.
   659→
   660→Furthermore they can use its Interface-based copy constructors and factories, _conversion constructors_ and _conversion factories_ and allow clients to choose the implementation type `public HashSet(Set set) -> TreeSet;`
   661→
   662→## 12. Consider implementing _Comparable_
   663→_Comparable_ is an interface. It is not declared in _Object_
   664→
   665→Sorting an array of objects that implement _Comparable_ is as simple as `Arrays.sort(a);`
   666→
   667→The class will interoperate with many generic algorithms and collection implementations that depend on this interface. You gain lot of power with small effort.
   668→
   669→Follow this provisions (Reflexive, Transitive, Symmetric):
   670→
   671→1.	`if a > b then b < a`  `if a == b then b == a`  `if a < b then b > a`
   672→2.	`if a > b and b > c then a > c`
   673→3.	`if a ==  b and b == c then a == c`
   674→4.	Strong suggestion: `a.equals(b) == a.compareTo(b)`
   675→
   676→For integral primitives use `<` and `>`operators.
   677→
   678→For floating-point fields use _Float.compare_ or _Double.compare_
   679→
   680→For arrays start with the most significant field and work your way down.
   681→
   682→# 4. CLASSES AND INTERFACES
   683→## 13. Minimize the accesibility of classes and members
   684→
   685→__Encapsulation__:
   686→
   687→* A well designed module hides all of its implementation details.
   688→* Separates its API from its implementation.
   689→* Decouples modules that comprise a system, allowing them to be isolated while:
   690→	* developed (can be developed in parallel)
   691→	* tested (individual modules may prove succesful even if the system does not)
   692→	* optimized and modified (no harm to other modules)
   693→	* understood (dont need other modules to be understood)
   694→	* used
   695→
   696→__Make each class or member as inaccesible as possible__
   697→
   698→If a package-private top level class is used  by only one class make it a  private nested class of the class that uses it. ([Item 22](#22-favor-static-member-classes-over-nonstatic))
   699→
   700→Is is acceptable to make a private member of a public class package-private in order to test it.
   701→
   702→__Instance fields should never be public__ ([Item 14](#14-in-public-classes-use-accessor-methods-not-public-fields)) Class will not be thread-safe.
   703→
   704→Static fields can be public if contain primitive values or references to immutable objects. A final field containing a reference to a mutable object has all the disadvantages of a non final field.
   705→
   706→Nonzero-length array is always mutable.
   707→
   708→```java
   709→
   710→	//Potential security hole!
   711→	public static final Thing[] VALUES = {...}
   712→```
   713→
   714→Solution:
   715→
   716→```java
   717→
   718→	private static final Thing[] PRIVATE_VALUES ={...}
   719→	public static final List<Thing> VALUES = Collections.unmodifiableList(Arrays.asList(PRIVATE_VALUES));
   720→```
   721→
   722→Or:
   723→
   724→```java
   725→
   726→	private static final Thing[] PRIVATE_VALUES ={...}
   727→	public static final Thing[] values(){
   728→		return PRIVATE_VALUES.clone;
   729→	}
   730→```
   731→
   732→## 14. In public classes, use accessor methods, not public fields
   733→
   734→Degenerate classes should not be public
   735→
   736→```java
   737→
   738→	class Point {
   739→		public double x;
   740→		public double y;
   741→	}
   742→```
   743→
   744→* The don't benefit from _encapsulation_ ([Item 13](#13-minimize-the-accesibility-of-classes-and-members))
   745→
   746→* Can't change representation without changing the API.
   747→
   748→* Can't enforce invariants.
   749→
   750→* Can't take auxiliary actions when a field is accessed.
   751→
   752→Replace them with _accessor methods_ (getters) and _mutators_ (setters).
   753→
   754→```java
   755→
   756→	class Point {
   757→		private double x;
   758→		private double y;
   759→
   760→		public Point(double x, double y){
   761→			this.x = x;
   762→			this.y = y;
   763→		}
   764→
   765→		public double getX() { return x; }
   766→		public double getY() { return y; }
   767→
   768→		public void setX(double x) { this.x = x; }
   769→		public void setY(double y) { this.y = y; }
   770→	}
   771→```
   772→
   773→If a class is accessed **outside its package**, provide **accesor methods**.
   774→
   775→If a class is **package-private or is a private nested class**, its **ok to expose** its data fields.
   776→
   777→In **public classes** it is a questionable option to **expose immutable fields**.
   778→
   779→
   780→
   781→## 15. Minimize Mutability
   782→All the information of the instance is provided when it is created.
   783→They are easier to design, implement and use. And they are less prone to errors and more secure
   784→
   785→* Don't provide any methods that modify the object's state (no mutators)
   786→* Ensure that the class can't be extended
   787→* Make all fields final
   788→* Make all fields private
   789→* Ensure exclusive access to any mutable component
   790→
   791→```java
   792→
   793→	public final class Complex {
   794→		private final double re;
   795→		private final double im;
   796→
   797→		public Complex (double re, double im) {
   798→			this.re = re;
   799→			this.im = im;
   800→		}
   801→
   802→		// Accessors with no corresponding mutators
   803→		public double realPart() { return re;}
   804→		public double imaginaryPart() { return im;}
   805→
   806→		public Complex add(Complex c){
   807→			return new Complex(re + c.re, im + c.im);
   808→		}
   809→
   810→		public Complex subtract(Complex c){
   811→			return new Complex(re - c.re, im - c.im);
   812→		}
   813→
   814→		...
   815→
   816→		@Override public boolean equals (Object o){...}
   817→	}
   818→
   819→```
   820→
   821→The arithmetic operation __create and return a new instance__. (Functional approach)
   822→
   823→Immutable objects are simple. They only have one state for its lifetime.
   824→
   825→Immutable objects are thread-safe. Synchronization is not required. They can be shared freely and can reuse existing instances.
   826→
   827→```java
   828→
   829→	public static final Complex ZERO = new Complex(0,0)
   830→	public static final Complex ONE = new Complex(1,0)
   831→	public static final Complex I = new Complex(0,1)
   832→```
   833→
   834→Using static factories can create constants of frequently requested instances and serve them in future requests.
   835→
   836→Internals of the immutable objects can also be share.
   837→
   838→They make great building blocks for other objects.
   839→
   840→The disadvantages is that require a separate object for distinct values. In some cases it could reach to a performance problem.
   841→
   842→__How to deny subclassing in immutable objects__
   843→
   844→1. Making it final
   845→
   846→2. Make all of its constructors private or package-private and add a public static factory
   847→
   848→```java
   849→
   850→	public class Complex {
   851→		private final double re;
   852→		private final double im;
   853→
   854→		private Complex (double re, double im){
   855→			this.re = re;
   856→			this.im = im;
   857→		}
   858→
   859→		public static Complex valueOf(double re, double im){
   860→			return new Complex(re,im);
   861→		}
   862→
   863→		...
   864→	}
   865→```
   866→
   867→This technique allows flexibility of multiple implementations, it's possible to tune  the performance and permit to create more factories with names that clarify its function.
   868→
   869→__Summary__
   870→
   871→Classes should be immutable unless there are good reasons to make them mutable.
   872→
   873→If a  class can not be immutable, limit its mutability as much as possible.
   874→
   875→Make every field final unles there is a good reason not to do it.
   876→
   877→Some of the rules can be lightened to improve performance (caching, lazy initialization...).
   878→
   879→## 16. Favor composition over inheritance
   880→Inheritance in this case is when a class extends another (_implementation inheritance_) Not interface inheritance.
   881→
   882→**Inheritance violates encapsulation**
   883→
   884→Fragility causes
   885→
   886→1. A subclass depends on the implementation details of its superclass. If the superclass change the subclass may break.
   887→
   888→2. The superclass can aquire new methods in new releases that might not be added in the subclass.
   889→
   890→**Composition**
   891→
   892→Instead of extending, give your new class a private field that references an instance of the existing class.
   893→
   894→Each instance method in the new class (_forwarding class_)invokes the corresponding method (_forwarding methods_) on the contained instance of the existing class and returns the results.
   895→
   896→
   897→**Wrapper (Decorator Pattern)**
   898→```java
   899→
   900→	// Wrapper class - uses composition in place of inheritance
   901→	public class InstrumentedSet<E> extends ForwardingSet<E> {
   902→		private int addCount = 0;
   903→		//It extends a class(inheritance),but it is a forwarding class that is actually a compositon of the Set
   904→		(specifically a forwarding class), not the Set itself.
   905→		public InstrumentedSet (Set<E> s){
   906→			super(s)
   907→		}
   908→
   909→		@Override
   910→		public boolean add(E e){
   911→			addCount++;
   912→			return super.add(e);
   913→		}
   914→
   915→		@Override
   916→		public boolean addAll (Collection< ? extends E> c){
   917→			addCount += c.size();
   918→			return super.addAll(c);
   919→		}
   920→
   921→		public int getAddCount() {
   922→			return addCount;
   923→		}
   924→	}
   925→```
   926→
   927→```java
   928→
   929→	// Reusable forwarding class
   930→	public class ForwardingSet<E> implements Set<E> {
   931→		private final Set<E> s; // Here is the composition. It uses the Set but not extends it.
   932→		public ForwardingSet(Set<E> s) { this.s = s ; }
   933→
   934→		// It implemets the Set, using the interface, and create the forwarding methods.
   935→		public void clear() {s.clear();}
   936→		public boolean contains(Object o) { return s.contains(o)}
   937→		...
   938→		public boolean add(E e) { return s.add(e)}
   939→		public boolean addAll (Collection< ? extends E> c){return s.addAll(c)}
   940→		...
   941→	}
   942→
   943→```
   944→
   945→## 17. Design and document for inheritance or else prohibit it.
   946→
   947→The class must document it _self-use_ of overridable methods.
   948→
   949→Methods and constructors should document which _overridable_ methods or constructors (nonfinal, and public or protected ) invokes. The description begins with the phrase "This implementation."
   950→
   951→To document  a class so that it can be safely subclassed, you must describe implementations details.
   952→
   953→To allow programmers to write efficient subclasses without undue pain, a class may have to provide hooks into its internal working in the form of judiciously chosen protected methods.
   954→
   955→__Test the class for subclassing__. The only way to test a class designed for inheritance is to write subclasses.
   956→
   957→Constructors must not invoke overridable methods. For _Serializable_ and  _Cloneable_ implementations neither _clone_ nor _readObject_ may  invoke overridable methods.
   958→
   959→Prohibit subclassing in classes that are not designed and documented to be safely subclassed. 2 options:
   960→
   961→* Declare the class final
   962→* Make all constructors private or package-private and add public static factories in place of the constructors.
   963→([Item 15](#15-minimize-mutability))
   964→
   965→Consider use [Item 16](#16-favor-composition-over-inheritance) if what you want is to increase the functionality of your class instead of subclassing.
   966→
   967→## 18. Prefer interfaces to abstract classes
   968→Java permits only single Inheritance, this restriction on abstract classes severely contrains their use as type functions.
   969→
   970→Intefaces is generally the best way to define a type that permits multiple implementations.
   971→
   972→Existing classes can be easily retrofitted to implement a new interface.
   973→
   974→Interfaces are ideal for defining mixins (a type that a class can implement in addition to its primary type to declare that it provides some optional bahaviour)
   975→
   976→Interfaces allow the construction of nonhierarchical type frameworks.
   977→
   978→Interfaces enable safe, powerful functionality enhancements (Wrapper class. [Item 16](#16-favor-composition-over-inheritance))
   979→
   980→Combine the virtues of interfaces and abstract classes, by providing an abstract **skeletal implementation** class to go with each **nontrivial interface** that you export.
   981→
   982→```java
   983→
   984→	//Concrete implementation built atop skeletal implementation
   985→	static List<Integer> intArrayAsList(final int[] a) {
   986→		if (a == null) throw new NullPointerException();
   987→
   988→
   989→		// From the documentation
   990→		//This class provides a skeletal implementation of the List interface to minimize the effort required to implement this interface backed by a "random access" data store (such as an array)
   991→		//To implement an unmodifiable list, the programmer needs only to extend this class and provide implementations for the get(int) and size() methods.
   992→		//To implement a modifiable list, the programmer must additionally override the set(int, E)
   993→
   994→		return new AbstractList<Integer>(){
   995→			public Integer get (int i){
   996→				return a[i]; // Autoboxing (Item 5)
   997→			}
   998→
   999→			@Override
  1000→			public Integer set(int i, Integer val){
  1001→				int oldVal = a[i];
  1002→				a[i] = val;		// Auto-unboxing
  1003→				return oldVal;	// Autoboxing
  1004→			}
  1005→
  1006→			public int size(){
  1007→				return a.length;
  1008→			}
  1009→		}
  1010→	}
  1011→```
  1012→Skeletal implementations are designed for inheritance so follow [Item 17](#17-design-and-document-for-inheritance-or-else-prohibit-it) guidelines.
  1013→
  1014→_simple implementation_ is like a skeletal implementation in that it implements the simplest possible working implementation.
  1015→
  1016→Cons: It is far easier to evolve an abstract class than an interface. Once an interface is released and widely implemented, it is almost impossible to change.
  1017→
  1018→## 19. Use interfaces only to define types
  1019→When a class implements an interface, the interface serves as a _type_ that can be used to refer to instances of the class.
  1020→
  1021→Any other use, like the _constant interface_ should be avoided.
  1022→
  1023→```java
  1024→
  1025→	// Constant interface antipattern
  1026→	public interface PhysicalConstants {
  1027→		static final double AVOGRADOS_NUMBER = 6.02214199e23;
  1028→		static final double BOLTZAN_CONSTANT = 1.3806503e-23;
  1029→		static final double ELECTRON_MASS = 9.10938188e-31;
  1030→	}
  1031→```
  1032→
  1033→Better use an enum type ([Item 31](#31-use-instance-fields-instead-of-ordinals)), or a noninstantiable _utility class_ ([Item 4](#4-enforce-noninstantiablillity-with-a-private-constructor))
  1034→
  1035→```java
  1036→
  1037→	//Constant utility class
  1038→	package com.effectivejava.science
  1039→
  1040→	public class PhysicalConstants{
  1041→		private PhysicalConstants(){} // Prevents instantiation
  1042→
  1043→		public static final double AVOGRADOS_NUMBER = 6.02214199e23;
  1044→		public static final double BOLTZAN_CONSTANT = 1.3806503e-23;
  1045→		public static final double ELECTRON_MASS = 9.10938188e-31;
  1046→	}
  1047→```
  1048→
  1049→To avoid the need of qualifying use _static import_.
  1050→
  1051→```java
  1052→
  1053→	//Use of static import to avoid qualifying constants
  1054→	import static com.effectivejava.science.PhysicalConstants.*
  1055→
  1056→	public class Test {
  1057→		double atoms(double mols){
  1058→			return AVOGRADOS_NUMBER * mols;
  1059→		}
  1060→		...
  1061→		// Many more uses of PhysicalConstants justify the static import
  1062→	}
  1063→```
  1064→
  1065→## 20. Prefer class hierarchies to tagged classes
  1066→Tagged classes are verbose, error-prone and inefficient.
  1067→
  1068→They have lot of boilerplate, bad readability, they increase memory footprint, and more shortcommings.
  1069→
  1070→```java
  1071→
  1072→	// Tagged Class
  1073→	class Figure{
  1074→		enum Shaple {RECTANGLE, CIRCLE};
  1075→
  1076→		final Shape shape;
  1077→
  1078→		// Rectangle fields
  1079→		double length;
  1080→		double width;
  1081→
  1082→		//Circle field
  1083→		double radius;
  1084→
  1085→		// Circle Constructor
  1086→		Figure (double radius) {
  1087→			shape = Shape.CIRCLE;
  1088→			this.radius=radius;
  1089→		}
  1090→
  1091→		// Rectangle Constructor
  1092→		Figure (double length, double width) {
  1093→			shape = Shape.RECTANGLE;
  1094→			this.length=length;
  1095→			this.width=width;
  1096→		}
  1097→
  1098→		double area(){
  1099→			switch(shape){
  1100→				case RECTANGLE:
  1101→					return length*width;
  1102→				case CIRCLE
  1103→					return Math.PI * (radius * radius);
  1104→				defalult
  1105→					throw new AssertionError();
  1106→			}
  1107→		}
  1108→	}
  1109→```
  1110→
  1111→A tagged class is just a palid imitation of a class hierarchy.
  1112→
  1113→* The code is simple and clear.
  1114→* The specific implementations are in its own class
  1115→* All fields are final
  1116→* The compiler ensures that each class's constructor initializes its data fields.
  1117→* Extendability and flexibility (Square extends Rectangle)
  1118→
  1119→```java
  1120→
  1121→	abstract class Figure{
  1122→		abstract double area();
  1123→	}
  1124→	class Circle extends Figure{
  1125→		final double radius;
  1126→
  1127→		Circle(double radius) { this.radius=radius;}
  1128→
  1129→		double area(){return Math.PI * (radius * radius);}
  1130→	}
  1131→	class Rectangle extends Figure{
  1132→		final double length;
  1133→		final double width;
  1134→
  1135→		Rectangle (double length, double width) {
  1136→			this.length=length;
  1137→			this.width=width;
  1138→		}
  1139→
  1140→		double area(){return length*width;}
  1141→	}
  1142→
  1143→	class Square extends Rectangle {
  1144→		Square(double side){
  1145→			super(side,side);
  1146→		}
  1147→	}
  1148→```
