  1150→## 21. Use function objects to represent strategies
  1151→Strategies are facilities that allow programs to store and transmit the ability to invoke a particular function. Similar to _function pointers_, _delegates_ or _lambda expression_.
  1152→
  1153→It is possible to define a object whose method perform operations on other objects.
  1154→
  1155→**Concrete strategy**
  1156→
  1157→```java
  1158→
  1159→	class StringLengthComparator{
  1160→		public int compare(String s1, String s2){
  1161→			return s1.length() - s2.length();
  1162→		}
  1163→	}
  1164→```
  1165→
  1166→Concrete strategies are typically _stateless_ threfore they should be singletons.
  1167→
  1168→To be able to pass different strategies, clients should invoke methods from an _strategy interface_ instead of from a concrete class.
  1169→
  1170→**Comparator interface.** _Generic_([Item 26](#26-favor-generic-types))
  1171→```java
  1172→
  1173→	public interface Comparator<T>{
  1174→		public int compare(T t1, T t2);
  1175→	}
  1176→```
  1177→
  1178→```java
  1179→
  1180→	class StringLengthComparator implements Comparator<String>{
  1181→		private StringLengthComparator(){} // Private constructor
  1182→		public static final StringLengthComparator INSTANCE = new StringLengthComparator(); // Singleton instance
  1183→		public int compare(String s1, String s2){
  1184→			return s1.length() - s2.length();
  1185→		}
  1186→	}
  1187→```
  1188→
  1189→Using **anonymous classes**
  1190→
  1191→```java
  1192→
  1193→	Arrays.sort(stringArray, new Comparator<String>(){
  1194→		public int compare(String s1, String s2){
  1195→			return s1.length() - s2.length();
  1196→		}
  1197→	})
  1198→```
  1199→
  1200→An anonymous class will create a new instance each time the call is executed. Consider a private static final field and reusing it.
  1201→
  1202→Concrete strategy class don't need to be public, because the strategy interface serve as a type.
  1203→A host class can export the a public static field or factory, whose type is the interface and the concrete strategy class is a private nested class.
  1204→
  1205→```java
  1206→
  1207→	// Exporting a concrete strategy
  1208→	class Host{
  1209→		private static class StringLengthComparator implements Comparator<String>, Serializable {
  1210→			public int compare(String s1, String s2){
  1211→				return s1.length() - s2.length();
  1212→			}
  1213→		}
  1214→
  1215→		//Returned comparator is serializable
  1216→		public static final Comparator<String> STRING_LEGTH_COMPARATOR = new StringLengthComparator();
  1217→
  1218→		...
  1219→	}
  1220→```
  1221→
  1222→## 22. Favor static member classes over nonstatic
  1223→4 types of nested classes.
  1224→
  1225→1. static
  1226→2. nonstatic
  1227→3. anonymous
  1228→4. local
  1229→
  1230→**Static**, a member class that does not require access to an enclosing instance must be _static_.  
  1231→
  1232→Storing references cost time, space and can cost not wanted behaviors of the garbage collector([Item 6](#6-eliminate-obsole-object-references))  
  1233→
  1234→Common use of static member class is a public helper in conjuctions with its outer class. A nested class enum _Operation_ in  _Calculator_ class. `Calculator.Operation.PLUS`;
  1235→
  1236→**Nonstatic** member class instances are required to have an enclosing instance.
  1237→
  1238→**Anonymous** classes are us to create _function objects_ on the fly. ([Item 21](#21-use-function-objects-to-represent-strategies))
  1239→
  1240→**Local** class from the official docs: Use it if you need to create more than one instance of a class, access its constructor, or introduce a new, named type (because, for example, you need to invoke additional methods later).
  1241→
  1242→Anonymous class, from the official docs: Use it if you need to declare fields or additional methods.
  1243→
  1244→
  1245→# 5. GENERICS
  1246→## 23. Don't use raw types in new code
  1247→Generic classes and interfaces are the ones who have one or more _type parameter_ as _generic_, i.e. `List<E>`
  1248→
  1249→Each generic type defines a set of _parametrized types_ `List<String>`
  1250→
  1251→_Raw types_ is the generic type definition without type parameters. `List`
  1252→
  1253→```java
  1254→
  1255→	private final Collection stamps = ...
  1256→
  1257→	stamps.add(new Coin(...)); //Erroneous insertion. Does not throw any error
  1258→
  1259→	Stamp s = (Stamp) stamps.get(i); // Throws ClassCastException when getting the Coin
  1260→```
  1261→
  1262→```java
  1263→
  1264→	private final Collection<Stamp> stamps = ...
  1265→
  1266→	stamps.add(new Coin()); // Compile time error. Coin can not be add to Collection<Stamp>
  1267→
  1268→	Stamp s = stamps.get(i); // No need casting
  1269→```
  1270→
  1271→Use of raw types lose safety and expressiveness of generics.
  1272→
  1273→Type safety is kept in a parametrized type like `List<Object>` but not in raw types (`List`).
  1274→
  1275→There are subtyping rules for generics. For example `List<String>` is a subtype of `List` but not of `List<Object>` ([Item 25](#25-prefer-lists-to-arrays))
  1276→
  1277→**Unbounded Wildcard Types `Set<?>`**
  1278→Used when a generic type is needed but we don't know or care the actual type.
  1279→
  1280→Never add elements (other than null) into a `Collection<?>`
  1281→
  1282→2 exceptions (because generic type information is erased at runtime):
  1283→
  1284→* Use raw types in class literals `List.class`,`String[].class` are legal, `List<String>.class`, `List<?>.class` are not.
  1285→* Use of instanceof
  1286→
  1287→```java
  1288→
  1289→	if (o instanceof Set){
  1290→		Set<?> = (Set<?>) o;
  1291→	}
  1292→```
  1293→
  1294→| **Term**                | **Example**                        |**Item**|
  1295→|-------------------------|------------------------------------|--------|
  1296→| Parametrized type       | `List<String>`                     | 23     |
  1297→| Actual type parameter   | `String`                           | 23     |
  1298→| Generic type            | `List<E>`                          | 23, 26 |
  1299→| Formal type parameter   | `E`                                | 23     |
  1300→| Unbounded wildcard type | `List<?>`                          | 23     |
  1301→| Raw type                | `List`                             | 23     |
  1302→| Bounded type parameter  | `<E extends Number>`               | 26     |
  1303→| Recursive type bound    | `<T extends Comparable<T>>`        | 27     |
  1304→| Bounded wildcard type   | `List<? extends Number>`           | 28     |
  1305→| Generic method          | `static <E> List<E> asList(E[] a)` | 27     |
  1306→| Type token              | `String.class`                     | 29     |
  1307→
  1308→## 24. Eliminate unchecked warnings
  1309→Eliminate every unchecked warning that you can, if you can´t use _Suppress-Warnings_ annotation on the smallest scope possible.
  1310→
  1311→```java
  1312→
  1313→	Set<Lark> exaltation = new HashSet(); Warning, unchecked convertion found.
  1314→	Set<Lark> exaltation = new HashSet<Lark>(); Good
  1315→```
  1316→
  1317→## 25. Prefer lists to arrays
  1318→Arrays are _covariant_: if `Sub` is a subtype of `Super`, `Sub[]` is a subtype of `Super[]`  
  1319→Generics are _invariant_: for any two types `Type1` and `Type2`, `List<Type1>` in neither  sub or super type of `List<Type1>`
  1320→
  1321→```java
  1322→
  1323→	// Fails at runtime
  1324→	Object[] objectArray = new Long[1];
  1325→	objectArray[0] ="I don't fit in" // Throws ArrayStoreException
  1326→
  1327→	// Won't compile
  1328→	List<Object> ol = new ArrayList<Long>();//Incompatible types
  1329→	ol.add("I don't fit in")
  1330→```
  1331→
  1332→Arrays are _reified_: Arrays know and enforce their element types at runtime.
  1333→Generics are _erasure_: Enforce their type constrains only at compile time and discard (or _erase_) their element type information at runtime.
  1334→
  1335→Therefore it is illegal to create an array of a generic type, a parameterized type or a type parameter.
  1336→
  1337→`new List<E>[]`, `new List<String>`, `new E[]`  will result in _generic array creation_ errors.
  1338→
  1339→## 26. Favor generic types
  1340→Making [Item 6](#6-eliminate-obsole-object-references) to use generics.
  1341→```java
  1342→
  1343→	public class Stack{
  1344→		private E[] elements;
  1345→		private int size = 0;
  1346→		private static final int DEFAULT_INITIAL_CAPACITY = 16;
  1347→
  1348→		public Stack(){
  1349→			elements = new E [DEFAULT_INITIAL_CAPACITY];//Error: Can't create an array of a non-reifiable type.
  1350→		}
  1351→
  1352→		public void push(E e){
  1353→			ensureCapacity();
  1354→			elements[size++] = e;
  1355→		}
  1356→
  1357→		public E pop(){
  1358→			if (size == 0)
  1359→				throw new EmptyStackException();
  1360→			E result = elements[--size];
  1361→			elements[size] = null;
  1362→			return result;
  1363→		}
  1364→		...
  1365→	}
  1366→```
  1367→
  1368→There will be one error:
  1369→
  1370→```java
  1371→
  1372→	//Error: Generic array creation. Can't create an array of a non-reifiable type.
  1373→	elements = new E [DEFAULT_INITIAL_CAPACITY];
  1374→```
  1375→**First option** (more commonly used.)
  1376→
  1377→```java
  1378→
  1379→	//Warning: Compiler can not prove the type safe, but we can.
  1380→	// This elements array will contain only E instances from push(E).
  1381→	// This is sifficient to ensure type safety, but the runtime
  1382→	//type of the array won't be E[]; it will always be Object[]!
  1383→	@SupressWarnings("unchecked")
  1384→	public Stack(){
  1385→		elements = (E[]) new Object [DEFAULT_INITIAL_CAPACITY];
  1386→	}
  1387→```
  1388→**Second Option**
  1389→```java
  1390→
  1391→	...
  1392→	private Object[] elements;
  1393→	...
  1394→	result = elements[--size] // Error: found Object, required E
  1395→```
  1396→A cast  will generate a warning. Beacuse E is a non-reifiable type, there is no way the compiler can check the cast at runtime.
  1397→```java
  1398→
  1399→	result = (E) elements[--size]
  1400→```
  1401→
  1402→The appropriate suppression of the unchecked warning
  1403→
  1404→```java
  1405→
  1406→	public E pop(){
  1407→		if (size == 0)
  1408→			throw new EmptyStackException();
  1409→
  1410→		// push requires elements to be of type E, so cast is correct.
  1411→		@SupressWarnings("unchecked") E result = elements[--size];
  1412→
  1413→		elements[size] = null;
  1414→		return result;
  1415→	}
  1416→```
  1417→
  1418→## 27. Favor generic Methods
  1419→Generic Method
  1420→```java
  1421→
  1422→	//
  1423→	public static <E> Set<E> union(Set<E> s1, Set<E> s2){
  1424→		Set<E> result = new HashSet<E>(s1);
  1425→		result.addAll(s2);
  1426→		return result;
  1427→	}
  1428→```
  1429→
  1430→**Type inference**: Compiler knows because of `Set<String>` that `E` is a _String_
  1431→
  1432→In generic constructors the type parameters have to be on both sides of the declaration. (Java 1.7 might have fix it)
  1433→
  1434→```java
  1435→
  1436→	Map<String,List<String>> anagrams = new HashMap<String, List<String>>();
  1437→```
  1438→
  1439→To avoid ic create a _generic static factory method_
  1440→
  1441→```java
  1442→
  1443→	public static <K,V> HashMap<K,V> newHashMap(){
  1444→		return new HashMap<K,V>();
  1445→	}
  1446→
  1447→	//Use
  1448→	Map<String,List<String>> anagrams = newHashMap();
  1449→
  1450→
  1451→```
  1452→
  1453→**Generic Singleton Pattern** Create an object that is immutable but applicable to many  different types.
  1454→
  1455→```java
  1456→
  1457→	public interface UnaryFunction<T>{
  1458→		T apply(T arg);
  1459→	}
  1460→
  1461→	// Generic singleton factory pattern
  1462→	private static UnaryFunction<Object> IDENTITY_FUNCTION = new UnaryFunction<Object>(){
  1463→		public Object apply(Object arg) {return arg;}
  1464→	};
  1465→
  1466→	//IDENTITY_FUNCTION is stateless and its type parameter is unbounded so it's safe to share one instance across all types.
  1467→	@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
  1468→	public static<T> UnaryFunction<T> identityFunction(){
  1469→		return(UnaryFunction<T>) IDENTITY_FUNCTION;
  1470→	}
  1471→```
  1472→
  1473→**Recursive Type Bound** : When the type paremeter is bounded by some expression involving that type parameter itself.
  1474→
  1475→```java
  1476→
  1477→	public static<T extends Comparable<T>> T max (List<T> list){
  1478→		Iterator <T> i = list.iterator():
  1479→		T result = i.next();
  1480→		while (i.hasNext()) {
  1481→			T t = i.next();
  1482→			if(t.compareTo(result) > 0)
  1483→				result = t;
  1484→		}
  1485→		return result;
  1486→	}
  1487→```
  1488→## 28. Use bounded wildcards to increase API flexibility
  1489→
  1490→
  1491→Parameterized types are invariant.([Item 25](#25-prefer-lists-to-arrays)) Ie `List<String>` is not a subtype of `List<Object>`
  1492→
  1493→```java
  1494→
  1495→	public void pushAll(Iterable<E> src){
  1496→		for(E e : src)
  1497→			puhs(e)
  1498→	}
  1499→
  1500→	// Integer is a subtype of Number

